From 665bdd50b4bab6c23ec274ab137a6936ecd49cbf Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Daniel Golle <daniel@makrotopia.org>
Date: Tue, 24 Feb 2026 23:16:08 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 19/24] lib: flush hash file between verity tree levels

On macOS (and other BSDs), writes to a FILE* are not immediately
visible to a separate FILE* opened on the same path because each
handle maintains its own userspace buffer and there is no unified
page cache like Linux.

The verity hash tree computation writes level N to hash_file, then
opens hash_file_2 to read it back for computing level N+1.  Without
an explicit fflush() between the write and the re-open, hash_file_2
reads stale (zero) data on macOS, producing an incorrect root hash.

Add fflush(hash_file) before opening hash_file_2 to ensure all
buffered data is written to disk.  This is a no-op on Linux where
the page cache already provides coherent views.
---
 lib/verity/verity_hash.c | 9 +++++++++
 1 file changed, 9 insertions(+)

--- a/lib/verity/verity_hash.c
+++ b/lib/verity/verity_hash.c
@@ -336,6 +336,15 @@ static int VERITY_create_or_verify_hash(
 			if (r)
 				goto out;
 		} else {
+			/*
+			 * Flush the write buffer before re-reading the hash
+			 * device through a second file handle.  On Linux the
+			 * unified page cache makes this optional; on macOS
+			 * and other BSDs, unflushed data is invisible to a
+			 * separate FILE* opened on the same path.
+			 */
+			fflush(hash_file);
+
 			hash_file_2 = fopen(device_path(crypt_metadata_device(cd)), "r");
 			if (!hash_file_2) {
 				log_err(cd, _("Cannot open device %s."),
